<text xml:lang="ta">
  <body>
    <div xml:id="PN397-intro">
      <p type="edition">tiṇai – pāṭāṇtiṇai. tuṟai – paricilviṭai; kaṭainilaiviṭaiyumām. cōḻaṉ kuḷaḻaṟṟattuttuñciya kiḷḷivaḷavaṉai erukkāṭṭūrt tāyaṅkaṇṇaṉār.
      </p>
      <p xml:lang="en" type="translation">  
      </p>
    </div>
    <div xml:id="PN397">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>veḷḷiyu miruvicum pērtarum puḷḷu</l>
<l>muyarciṉaik kuṭampaik kuraṟṟōṟ ṟiṉavē</l>
<l>poykaiyum pōtukaṇ viḻittaṉa paipayac</l>
<l>cuṭaruñ curuṅkiṉ ṟoḷiyē pāṭeḻun</l>
<l>tiraṅkukuraṉ muracamoṭu valampuri yārppa</l>
<l>viravuppuṟaṅ kaṇṭa kālait tōṉṟi</l>
<l>yeḵkiru ḷakaṟṟu mēmap pācaṟai</l>
<l>vaikaṟai yaravaṅ kēḷiyar palakōṭ</l>
<l>ceytār mārpa veḻumati tuyileṉat</l>
<l>teṇkaṇ mākkiṇai teḷirppa voṟṟi</l>
<l>neṭuṅkaṭait tōṉṟi yēṉē yatunayan</l>
<l>tuḷḷi vanta paricila ṉivaṉeṉa</l>
<l>neyyuṟap poritta kuyyuṭai neṭuñcūṭu</l>
<l>maṇikkala ṉiṟainta maṇanāṟu tēṟal</l>
<l>pāmpurit taṉṉa vāṉpūṅ kaliṅkamoṭu</l>
<l>māri yaṉṉa vaṇmaiyiṟ corintu</l>
<l>vēṉi laṉṉaveṉ veppu nīṅka</l>
<l>varuṅkala nalki yōṉē yeṉṟuñ</l>
<l>ceṟuviṟ pūtta cēyitaḻt tāmarai</l>
<l>yaṟutoḻi lantaṇa raṟampurin teṭutta</l>
<l>tīyoṭu viḷaṅku nāṭaṉ vāyvāḷ</l>
<l>valampaṭu tīviṟ polampūṇ vaḷava</l>
<l>ṉeṟitiraip peruṅkaṭa liṟutikkaṭ celiṉun</l>
<l>teṟukatirk kaṉali teṉṟicait tōṉṟiṉu</l>
<l>meṉṉeṉ ṟañcalam yāmē veṉvē</l>
<l>laruñcamaṅ kaṭakku māṟṟalavaṉ</l>
<l>ṟiruntukaḻa ṉōṉṟāṭ taṇṇiḻa lēmē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l corresp="1">Venus rises in the dark sky and the birds, </l>
<l corresp="2">made heard [their] voice from the nests in high branches, </l>
<l corresp="3">and in the ponds buds opened [their] eyes gently </l>
<l corresp="4">and the sun shrunk in light. As singing rises, </l>
<l corresp="5">as right-spiralling conched roar together with resonant drums, </l>
<l corresp="6">appearing at the time when one sees the back of the night, </l>
<l corresp="7">in the protected war camp that repels the darkness with blades </l>
<l corresp="8">“may you listen to the sounds of dawn, for takings that are many, </l>
<l corresp="9">you whose chest has a [well]made garland, rise from sleep”, so saying, </l>
<l corresp="10">pressing so that it sounds [my] clear-eyed big Kiṇai drum </l>
<l>I have appeared at the tall gate. “this one is a solicitor</l>
<l>who came, longing for that [and] remembering”, so saying, (11f.)</l>
<l corresp="13">a tall rost with seasoning that was fried while it had ghee, </l>
<l corresp="14">clarified toddy fragrant with scent that filled a bejewelled vessel, </l>
<l corresp="15">together with a white flowery Kaliṅkam cloth that was like a snake skin </l>
<l corresp="16">– pouring [his] bounty like the showers, </l>
<l corresp="17">so that my heat that was like the summer left, </l>
<l corresp="18">he is the one who granted precious ornaments, always </l>
<l corresp="19">a lotus with red petals that bloomed in the field, </l>
<l corresp="21a-c">the man from a land that shine with the fires </l>
<l corresp="20">raised, acting in accordance with dharma, by brahmins with six tasks, </l>
<l corresp="21d">	[his] sword excellent, </l>
<l corresp="22">benefactor with golden ornaments, like an island where fertility happens. </l>
<l corresp="23">Even if we fo to the end of the great sea with dashing waves, </l>
<l corresp="24">even if the sun with scorching rays appears in the southern directions, </l>
<l corresp="25a-c">we will not be afraid, saying “what?”, </l>
<l corresp="27">we who are in the cool shade of his sturdy feet with perfect anklets, </l>
<l corresp="25d-26">[he] capable of winning difficult fights with [his] victorious spear. </l>
</lg>
